    "body": "### Problem\n\nC'mon, 2025 knocks the door, and I still only have **old** Neovim 0.7 in that forgotten Ubuntu PPA for Aarch64/ARM32 and no Neovim on Arm for Fedora at all unless I compile it myself. Time to provide official ARM releases on every major platform, be it Linux, Windows, or macOS. Right now, I see only macOS support. Is it that difficult to tweak GitHub Actions files, especially given that ARM source releases compile flawlessly? Even if I have to download the RPM/DEBs from the Releases page, it's still much better than compiling from the source.\nWhat if I want to tweak some configs quickly on my Raspberry Pi, or code on a phone (in fact, I do), or for unbeknownst reasons have a shiny new X Elite laptop?\nAnyway, ARM is the future. Even such behemoth projects like Blender provide ARM builds in alpha testing.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nI can just `sudo apt install neovim` or `sudo dnf install neovim` regardless of whether I use ARM or x86. GitHub Actions can handle cross-compilation easily.",
